        To make use of the stat testing system, inherit STAT_TEST;
in any room, object, or monster.  You can perform a test with the
following syntax test_<stat>(<difficulty>,<subject>);.  It is an integer
function which will return by how much the test was passed or failed.
Remember if a player exactly makes the number needed, 0 will be returned,
not 1.  The difficulty should be a number between 1 and 100, with higher
numbers meaning harder tests.  If it is not supplied, 50 will be assumed.
Subject should be the object to perform the test on.  If not supplied,
this_player() will be assumed.  A few examples:
 
test_str();
test_int(25);
test_chr(90,this_player()->query_attack());
 
        The first will perform a default level 50 test on
this_player()'s strength.  The second will perform an easier level 25
test on the player's intelligence, and the last will make an extremely
difficult charisma test on the monster the player is attacking.  For some
examples of objects using tests, check /open/OBJ/stat_mace and stat_goblin.
 
        The inheritable stat testing system takes a number of things
into account, including that no test will ALWAYS succeed or ALWAYS fail,
and that the differences between a stat of 11 and 12 should be more
dramatic than between 47 and 48.  It can be used to reward players who
have kept rell rounded characters, and make statistics not vital to
combat or spell points still important.  You can use charisma tests to
determine the reactions of NPCs, dexterity tests to perform leaping or
climbing, wisdom or intelligence tests to read books or successfully
search, etc.  Consider using appropriate stat tests instead of pure
random numbers in your code.
 
